      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! Let's break down **k-nearest-neighbor (kNN)** and why it's so important in FeatureMAP.\n\n---\n\n### What is kNN in simple terms?\n\nThink of each cell in your dataset as a point in a high-dimensional \"gene-space\" — imagine a huge map where every cell has a location based on which genes are turned on or off.  \n\n**kNN** is a way to answer: *\"Who are the k closest neighbors to this cell?\"*  \n\n- You pick a number **k** (e.g., 15 or 30).  \n- For each cell, you find the **k other cells** that are most similar (closest in gene-expression space).  \n- You connect each cell to its nearest neighbors with an imaginary line.\n\nResult: a network (graph) where cells are nodes and edges link nearby cells.\n\n**Analogy**: Imagine a crowd of people in a park. For each person, you grab the 10 people standing closest to them and link arms. Now you have a web of connections that shows the local structure of the crowd — who is near whom, and where groups form.\n\n---\n\n### How does FeatureMAP use kNN?\n\nFeatureMAP uses the kNN graph as the **scaffolding to understand the shape (manifold) of the data**. Here's the step-by-step role:\n\n1. **Approximate the manifold**  \n   Single-cell data lives on a curved, low-dimensional \"surface\" (manifold) inside a high-dimensional space. The kNN graph is a discrete approximation of that surface — it tells us which cells are locally connected.\n\n2. **Compute local tangent spaces**  \n   For each cell, FeatureMAP takes its k nearest neighbors and performs **PCA** (via SVD) on that small group. This gives:\n   - **Principal directions** (the \"axes\" that best describe variation among those neighbors).  \n   - **Anisotropic radii** (how spread out the neighbors are in each direction).  \n\n   These principal directions define a **tangent space** — a flat, local approximation of the curved manifold around that cell.\n\n3. **Enable the two key embeddings**  \n   - **GEX embedding**: Uses the kNN graph + local radii to preserve cell density (how tightly packed cells are).  \n   - **GVA embedding**: Uses the tangent directions (from kNN neighborhoods) to preserve how gene expression changes directionally as cells move along trajectories.\n\n---\n\n### Why can't we just use all cells? Why kNN?\n\nIf we used all cells at once, we'd get a global view that ignores local structure. kNN keeps things **local** — it respects that cells only interact with nearby neighbors. This is crucial for:\n- Capturing fine-grained transitions (e.g., a cell slowly turning into another type).  \n- Preserving the curvature and topology of the manifold (bends, branches, etc.).\n\n---\n\n### In one sentence\n\n**kNN serves FeatureMAP by building a local neighborhood graph that allows the method to estimate the direction and shape of gene changes cell-by-cell, while ignoring distant, irrelevant cells.**\n\nDoes that help clarify? If you'd like a concrete example with numbers or a sketch, I can walk through that too!"
